 why are we creating this function couldnt we access the bool declaration using dot operator without it? 
    bool IsComplete() const { return isComplete; }

You could certainly make isComplete a public member and access it with textBox.isComplete. However, the primary reason for having a function like IsComplete() is to adhere to good object-oriented design principles, specifically encapsulation. Here‚Äôs why:

‚Ä¢ Encapsulation (keeping data private): If the class fields (like isComplete) stay private, you maintain control over how they are accessed or modified. Later on, if you decide to add extra logic whenever you check isComplete‚Äîlike logging usage, triggering events, or performing additional checks‚Äîyou can do so directly inside the IsComplete() function without changing any external code.

‚Ä¢ Ensuring read-only access when desired: Providing a const function that returns a private member is a simple way to allow read-only access. If isComplete were public, nothing would stop other parts of the code from mistakenly modifying it.

‚Ä¢ Future flexibility: If you want to rename or remove isComplete altogether later on, you can keep the IsComplete() function return type or logic consistent (thus not breaking your entire codebase).

So, while it‚Äôs not wrong to make isComplete public and access it directly, having an accessor function is a common practice that keeps your class flexible and well-encapsulated.
