Yes, you could move that input check (if (IsKeyPressed(KEY_SPACE) && textBox.IsComplete())) inside the class update logic if you want. However, there are a couple of design details to consider:

‚Ä¢ Separation of Concerns: Typically, you keep game-loop input checks outside the class, and let the class focus on its core functionality. That way, your TextWindow class doesn‚Äôt need to ‚Äúknow‚Äù about input devices or keys; it just needs to handle drawing text.  
‚Ä¢ Extensibility: If later you decide to trigger the reset from a controller button press or a UI event, you wouldn‚Äôt have to modify your class; you‚Äôd just call Reset() externally.

In a small or simpler project, it‚Äôs perfectly fine to move the input check inside TextWindow::Update() for ‚Äúcleaner‚Äù code. Just be aware that it couples your TextWindow class to specific input logic. If you‚Äôre comfortable with that or the project is small, go ahead. Otherwise, keep it external for flexibility.
