Below is an example of how you can organize a single DialogWindow class so it (1) manages its own text strings, (2) handles input to move to the next string, and (3) draws itself. This is not the most ‚Äúpure‚Äù design (because you generally keep input or higher-level game logic outside of the class), but it shows everything in one place.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
DialogWindow.hpp
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

#pragma once
#include "raylib.h"
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include "globals.h"

class DialogWindow {
public:
    // Constructor can load up a default set of messages
    DialogWindow(int posX, int posY, int w, int h, const std::vector<std::string>& messages)
        : x(posX), y(posY), width(w), height(h), 
          allMessages(messages), currentMessage(0) 
    {
        // Immediately set fullText to the first message if there's at least one
        if (!allMessages.empty()) {
            fullText = allMessages[currentMessage];
        }
    }

    // Main update function
    void Update() {
        // Only update character-by-character logic if there's a valid message
        if (!allMessages.empty() && currentMessage < (int)allMessages.size()) {
            if (!isComplete) {
                // Timer logic
                timer += GetFrameTime(); 
                // Reveal next character if enough time has passed
                if (timer >= charDelay && currentChar < (int)fullText.size()) {
                    currentText += fullText[currentChar];
                    currentChar++;
                    timer = 0.0f;
                }
                // Check if the entire message is shown
                if (currentChar >= (int)fullText.size()) {
                    isComplete = true;
                }
            }

            // If the user presses SPACE and the current message is fully shown,
            // move on to the next message
            if (IsKeyPressed(KEY_SPACE) && isComplete) {
                currentMessage++;
                if (currentMessage < (int)allMessages.size()) {
                    Reset(allMessages[currentMessage]);
                }
                else {
                    // No more messages ‚Äî optionally do something here.
                    // E.g., set a flag or keep isComplete = true
                }
            }
        }
    }

    // Draw the dialog rectangle and its text
    void Draw() {
        DrawRectangle(x, y, width, height, hellRed);       // assumed color from globals.h
        DrawRectangleLines(x, y, width, height, BLACK);
        DrawText(currentText.c_str(), x + 10, y + 10, 20, BLUE);
    }

    bool IsComplete() const { return isComplete; }

    // Whether we've exhausted all messages
    bool AllMessagesShown() const {
        return (currentMessage >= (int)allMessages.size());
    }

private:
    // Private so that only this class can manage these values
    int x;
    int y;
    int width;
    int height;

    // The entire list of messages we want to display in sequence
    std::vector<std::string> allMessages;

    // The message currently being displayed
    std::string fullText;
    // The substring that has already been revealed
    std::string currentText;

    // Character reveal timing
    float timer = 0.0f;
    float charDelay = 0.05f; // seconds per character
    int currentChar = 0;
    bool isComplete = false;

    // Index of the currently displayed message in allMessages
    int currentMessage;

    // Reset the dialog to a new message
    void Reset(const std::string& newMessage) {
        fullText = newMessage;
        currentText.clear();
        currentChar = 0;
        timer = 0.0f;
        isComplete = false;
    }
};

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Explanation and Notes
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. Constructor with std::vector<std::string>& messages  
   ‚Ä¢ DialogWindow loads a vector of strings (allMessages).  
   ‚Ä¢ Sets the first message (fullText) to allMessages[0] if available.  

2. Update Logic  
   ‚Ä¢ If the current message is not fully revealed, the timer accumulates from GetFrameTime().  
   ‚Ä¢ Once timer ‚â• charDelay, append the next character from fullText to currentText.  
   ‚Ä¢ If all characters are shown, isComplete = true.  
   ‚Ä¢ If the user presses space and isComplete == true, then we move on to the next message by calling Reset().  

3. Draw Logic  
   ‚Ä¢ DrawRectangle for the background.  
   ‚Ä¢ DrawRectangleLines for the border.  
   ‚Ä¢ DrawText of currentText, which is the partially revealed text.  

4. AllMessagesShown()  
   ‚Ä¢ In some scenarios, you might want to know when all messages have been displayed. This function checks if currentMessage >= allMessages.size().  

5. Private Data  
   ‚Ä¢ x, y, width, height define the window position and size.  
   ‚Ä¢ allMessages holds all the text lines we want to display in sequence.  
   ‚Ä¢ fullText is the entire text of the current message, while currentText is the substring that‚Äôs been revealed so far.  
   ‚Ä¢ currentMessage is the index of the current message within allMessages.  
   ‚Ä¢ timer, charDelay, and currentChar control the reveal pacing.  

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Usage Example
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

#include "raylib.h"
#include "DialogWindow.hpp"

int main() {
    InitWindow(800, 600, "Dialog Demo");
    SetTargetFPS(60);

    // Suppose we define messages for our first level
    std::vector<std::string> levelDialog = {
        "Welcome to level 1!",
        "This is your first challenge.",
        "Remember to press space to continue.",
        "Good luck, trainer!"
    };

    // Create a dialog window at position (100,400), size (600,150).
    // Pass it the messages we want to display.
    DialogWindow dialog(100, 400, 600, 150, levelDialog);

    while (!WindowShouldClose()) {
        // Update the dialog window logic (includes input checking).
        dialog.Update();

        BeginDrawing();
        ClearBackground(RAYWHITE);

        // Draw the dialog window
        dialog.Draw();

        // If we want to do something when all messages are shown,
        // we can check dialog.AllMessagesShown().
        if (dialog.AllMessagesShown()) {
            // e.g., Draw something else or proceed to next state
        }

        EndDrawing();
    }

    CloseWindow();
    return 0;
}

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Summary
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
This setup keeps all logic in a single class:  
‚Ä¢ The constructor takes a vector of messages.  
‚Ä¢ Update() handles the character reveal and space key to advance messages.  
‚Ä¢ Draw() displays a background rectangle plus the text.  
‚Ä¢ The class can check if everything is finished with AllMessagesShown().  

Feel free to adjust the design to better separate concerns‚Äîfor example, removing the input check from the class and letting some external game manager handle user input. But if your goal is everything in one place, the above is a viable approach.
